'''''Ailanthus altissima''''', commonly known as '''Tree of Heaven''', simply '''Ailanthus''', or in Chinese as '''Chouchun''' ({{zh-stp|s=臭椿|t=臭椿|p=chòuchūn}}), is a [[deciduous]] tree in the [[Simaroubaceae|quassia family]]. It is native to northeastern and central [[China]] as well as [[Taiwan]]. An exceptional member of the genus, it is found in temperate climates rather than the tropics like all the other ''Ailanthus'' species. The tree grows rapidly and has been found to reach heights of 15 metres (50 feet) in just 25 years.<ref name="USDF">{{cite web| last =Miller| first =James H.| authorlink =| coauthors =Yawney, Harry W. | title =Ailanthus altissima| work = Silvics of Forest Trees of the United States, Volume 2| publisher = United States Department of Forestry| date =1965, revised December 1990| url =http://na.fs.fed.us/pubs/silvics_manual/volume_2/ailanthus/altissima.htm| format =| doi =| accessdate =2007-05-29}}</ref> However, they are also short lived and rarely reach beyond 50 years in age. The common name as well as the genus are derived from an East Indian word ''aylanto'', meaning "heaven-tree" or "tree reaching for the sky". Other common names include china sumac, copal tree, stinktree and ghetto palm.

''A. altissima'' has been introduced to many areas beyond its native range, in many of which it has become a serious invasive species. The plant was first brought to [[Europe]] in 1751 by the French [[Jesuit]] Pierre Nicholas d'Incarville, who sent seeds to [[England]] from [[Nanking]]. It was initially received positively, for during this time Chinese taste was already popular in European architecture, furniture and porcelain design: the so called ''chinoiserie''. Furthermore, the tree of heaven was one of the first trees introduced from China, making it a very exotic garden specimen. The tree was introduced into the [[United States]] in 1784 by William Hamilton, a [[Philadelphia]] plant collector, along with other Chinese trees such as [[Ginkgo]]. Shortly after its introduction it began to be seen in a more negative light due to its suckering habits and it's offensive odour, though it was a popular street tree during much of the 19th century. <ref name="harvard">{{cite journal| last =Shah| first =Behula| authorlink =| coauthors =| title = The Checkered Career of ''Ailanthus altissima'' | journal =Arnoldia
  | volume =57
  | issue =3
  | pages =
  | publisher = Harvard University Press
  | date =Summer 1997
  | url =http://arnoldia.arboretum.harvard.edu/pdf/articles/472.pdf
  | doi =
  | id =
  | accessdate =2007-05-29}}</ref>As of the present time, the tree has become established in all but 6 U.S. states. 

==Description==
[[Image:Ailanthus altissima1.jpg|thumb|left|Seeds]]
''A. altissima'' is a medium-size tree that reaches heights between 17 and 27 metres (56 and 90 feet) with a  diameter at breast height of about 1 metre (40 inches).<ref name=USDF/> The [[bark]] is smooth and light grey, often becoming somewhat rougher with light tan fissures as the tree ages. The twigs are stout, smooth to lightly pubescent and reddish or chestnut in colour. They have lenticels as well as heart shaped leaf scars with many bundle scars around the margin. The [[bud]]s are finely pubescent, dome shaped, and partially hidden behind the petiole, though they are completley visible in the dormant season at the sinuses of the leaf scars.<ref name=harvard2/> The branches are light to dark gray in colour, smooth, lustrous and containing raised lenticels the become fissures with age. They are pendulous at the distal ends.  All parts of the plant have a strong odour that is often likened to rotting peanuts or cashews, which distinguishes the species from similar plants.<ref name=invasive>{{cite web
  | last =Miller
  | first =James H.
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title =Tree-of-heaven
  | work =Nonnative invasive plants of southern forests: a field guide for identification and control.
  | publisher =
  | date =2003
  | url =http://www.invasive.org/eastern/srs/TofH.html
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate =2007-05-29}}</ref> 

The [[leaf|leaves]] are large, odd or even pinnately compound, and arranged alternately on the stem. They range in size from 30 to 90 cm (1 to 3 feet) in length, with the largest leaves being present on vigorous young sprouts, and contain 10-41 leaflets. The [[rachis]] is light to reddish green with swollen bases. The [[leaflet]]s are ovate-lanceolate with entire margins, somewhat asymmetric and ocassionly not directly opposite on another. Each leaflet is 5 to 18 cm (2 to 7 inches) long and 2.5 to 5 cm (1 to 2 inches) wide. They have a long tapering apex, while the bases have 2 to 4 gladular teeth, each containing one or more glands at the tip.<ref name="harvard2">{{cite journal| last =Hu| first =Shiu-ying| authorlink =| coauthors =| title = ''Ailanthus altissima'' | journal =Arnoldia
  | volume =39
  | issue =2
  | pages =29-50
  | publisher = Harvard University Press
  | date =March 1979
  | url =http://arnoldia.arboretum.harvard.edu/pdf/articles/1072.pdf
  | doi =
  | id =
  | accessdate =2007-05-30}}</ref> The leaflets are a dark green in colour above with light green veins, while the undersides are a more whitish green. The [[petiole]]s are 5 to 12 mm (0.2 to 0.5 inches) long.<ref name=invasive/> The lobed bases and glands distinguish it from similar [[rhus|sumac]] species.

The [[flower]]s are small and appear in large [[panicle]]s up to 50 cm (20 inches) in length at the end of new shoots. The individual flowers are yellowish green to reddish in colour, each with 5 [[petal]]s and 5 [[sepal]]s.<ref name=USDF/><ref name=invasive/> They appear from mid-April in the south of its range to July in the north. ''A. altissima'' is [[plant sexuality|dioecious]], with male and female flowers being borne on different individuals. Male trees produce three to four times as many flowers as the females, making the male flowers more conspicuous. Furthermore, the males emit a foul smelling odour while flowering to attract pollinating insects. Female flowers contain 10 (or rarely 5 through abortion) sterile [[stamen]]s, or stamenoides, as well as 5 carpels with a slender styles and star-shaped stigmas.<ref name=harvard2/> The [[seed]]s borne on the female trees are 5 mm in diameter and each is encapsulated in a [[Samara (fruit)|samara]] that is 2.5 cm long (1 inch) and 1 cm broad, appearing July though August, but usually persisting on the tree until the next spring. The samara is twisted at the tips making it spin as it falls and assisting wind dispersal.<ref name=USDF/><ref name=invasive/> The females can produce huge amounts of seeds, normally around 30,000 per kilogram of tree tree.<ref name=USDF/>

==Taxonomy==
There are two [[variety (biology)|varieties]] of ''A. altissima'':
*''A. altissima'' var. ''altissima'', which is the type variety and is native in [[mainland China]].
*''A. altissima'' var. ''tanakai'', which is endemic in northern [[Taiwan]] at medium to high altitudes. It differs from the type in having yellowish bark, odd-pinnate leaves that are also shorter on average at 45 to 60 cm long with only 13-25 leaflets.<ref name=taiwan>{{cite web
  | last =Li
  | first =Hui-lin
  | authorlink =
